1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:03,573
Last year, everyone shipped AI into production.

2
00:00:03,573 --> 00:00:07,169
This year, everyone is discovering the same ugly thing.

3
00:00:07,169 --> 00:00:09,980
AI quality doesn't fail loudly — it drifts.

4
00:00:09,980 --> 00:00:12,399
A retrieval index goes quietly stale.

5
00:00:12,399 --> 00:00:14,491
A model update changes behavior.

6
00:00:14,491 --> 00:00:17,826
And nobody notices until customers do — days later.

7
00:00:17,826 --> 00:00:24,560
Your dashboards logged all of it and told you nothing, because every single response still looked fine.

8
00:00:24,560 --> 00:00:28,155
We built DRIFT: the early-warning court for AI quality.

9
00:00:30,055 --> 00:00:38,014
DRIFT watches your AI's answers in production and scores every one — quality, hedging, truncation, retrieval hits, latency.

10
00:00:38,014 --> 00:00:40,860
What you're seeing is a healthy support bot.

11
00:00:40,860 --> 00:00:42,025
Boring on purpose.

12
00:00:42,025 --> 00:00:48,883
But here's what makes DRIFT different from every observability tool: DRIFT never trusts its own suspicion.

13
00:00:48,883 --> 00:00:52,765
Before anything alerts a human, the suspicion goes on trial.

14
00:00:57,055 --> 00:01:00,293
Degradation has started — planted retrieval decay.

15
00:01:00,293 --> 00:01:04,956
Notice: every individual response still passes any reasonable threshold.

16
00:01:04,956 --> 00:01:09,230
This is the failure mode that kills every threshold-based monitor.

17
00:01:09,230 --> 00:01:10,849
So DRIFT holds a hearing.

18
00:01:10,849 --> 00:01:17,261
A prosecutor argues the decline is real — armed with regression the code computed, never the model.

19
00:01:17,261 --> 00:01:23,283
A defense attacks with every innocent explanation: did traffic shift toward harder questions?

20
00:01:23,283 --> 00:01:24,384
One outlier user?

21
00:01:24,384 --> 00:01:25,161
Time of day?

22
00:01:25,161 --> 00:01:26,003
Scorer noise?

23
00:01:26,003 --> 00:01:27,039
Too few samples?

24
00:01:27,039 --> 00:01:30,083
And a judge rules on a fixed standard of proof.

25
00:01:30,083 --> 00:01:30,601
Our C.I.

26
00:01:30,601 --> 00:01:31,767
proves this works.

27
00:01:31,767 --> 00:01:47,115
Three fixture streams run on every commit: the court must convict planted drift, must acquit pure noise — and must acquit the hard case: a traffic-mix shift where the aggregate trend is genuinely negative, but nothing is actually broken.

28
00:01:47,115 --> 00:01:51,584
That acquittal is a machine-checked claim, public in our Actions tab.

29
00:01:51,584 --> 00:01:56,505
Every alert-fatigue horror story you've heard is that third case, unhandled.

30
00:01:58,055 --> 00:02:00,796
The trend just survived cross-examination.

31
00:02:00,796 --> 00:02:05,038
Now — and this is the product — DRIFT doesn't hand you a red dot.

32
00:02:05,038 --> 00:02:06,669
It hands you a countdown.

33
00:02:06,669 --> 00:02:11,237
Quality crosses your floor in three to five hours at the current rate.

34
00:02:11,237 --> 00:02:13,326
Probable cause: retrieval decay.

35
00:02:13,326 --> 00:02:17,567
Hours of warning, a cause to investigate, and a confidence range.

36
00:02:17,567 --> 00:02:23,245
Pure deterministic math — a language model never produces a number this system acts on.

37
00:02:23,245 --> 00:02:27,291
And when the fit is too weak to trust, DRIFT refuses to guess.

38
00:02:27,291 --> 00:02:28,465
A range is honest.

39
00:02:28,465 --> 00:02:31,402
A confident number from a bad fit is theater.

40
00:02:46,055 --> 00:02:48,195
Every forecaster demos well once.

41
00:02:48,195 --> 00:02:50,334
So DRIFT grades itself in public.

42
00:02:50,334 --> 00:02:58,437
Here's the predicted crossing window laid over what actually happened — the real crossing landed inside the predicted window.

43
00:02:58,437 --> 00:03:04,661
The alert's outcome is backfilled into the ledger, and the dashboard shows live alert precision.

44
00:03:04,661 --> 00:03:08,161
No monitoring vendor shows you their false-alarm rate.

45
00:03:08,161 --> 00:03:10,171
We made it the headline metric.

46
00:03:12,055 --> 00:03:13,222
Who pays for this?

47
00:03:13,222 --> 00:03:15,490
Anyone whose AI talks to customers.

48
00:03:15,490 --> 00:03:30,135
A support bot doing ten thousand conversations a day that quietly degrades for three days is thirty thousand bad customer experiences — refunds, escalations to human agents at dollars per ticket, and churn you can't attribute.

49
00:03:30,135 --> 00:03:34,088
DRIFT turns that into a two-hour incident with a named cause.

50
00:03:34,088 --> 00:03:39,466
LangSmith, Arize, Braintrust — excellent tools that tell you what your quality was.

51
00:03:39,466 --> 00:03:44,067
None of them forecast, and none of them cross-examine their own alarms.

52
00:03:44,067 --> 00:03:49,445
DRIFT ships both, and self-reports its precision — a metric no incumbent publishes.

53
00:03:51,055 --> 00:03:55,862
And this is why AMD matters — not as a sponsor logo, but as the economics.

54
00:03:55,862 --> 00:04:04,046
Scoring every response, plus two extra reasoning passes per suspicion, is exactly the workload per-token API pricing punishes.

55
00:04:04,046 --> 00:04:10,931
On one MI300X, 192 gigabytes of memory holds our sensing model and the judge simultaneously, at flat cost.

56
00:04:10,931 --> 00:04:16,777
Adversarial verification is the feature incumbents can't afford to build on API economics.

57
00:04:16,777 --> 00:04:20,674
Our moat is partly a hardware-cost artifact — and we say so.

58
00:04:20,674 --> 00:04:30,936
Everything you saw is live: real models, one-command onboarding onto any OpenAI-compatible endpoint — including a vLLM box on AMD Developer Cloud — and a C.I.

59
00:04:30,936 --> 00:04:34,898
tab that machine-checks the court's judgment on every commit.

60
00:04:34,898 --> 00:04:36,912
AI quality doesn't fail loudly.

61
00:04:36,912 --> 00:04:39,770
Now it doesn't have to fail silently either.

62
00:04:39,770 --> 00:04:42,108
DRIFT — verdict first, alert second.
